"Take subnet 1 maintained by Opentensor as an example, what does this subnet that supposedly allows better models to emerge do? Simply put, the grid allows verifiers to create topics via Wikipedia API, StackOverflow, mathgenerator and other APIs, and then input the topics into GPT to create prompts, which are then distributed to nearly 1,000 miners in the subgrid, who then use GPT or other LLMs to create an answer. After receiving the prompt, the miner calls GPT or other LLMs to create an answer and returns it to the verifier. When the verifier gets the answer, he or she will compare the similarity of the answer with the reference answer (which was also created using GPT) and score the miner.
What is the point of such a sub-grid? It is not a waste of OpenAI's or other LLM providers' computation and the cost of supporting the API. The questions are randomly created, such as a high school math question created from the mathgenerator website and LLM-organized language; the miner's answer is created from an external LLM, and the verifier's reference answer is created from LLM, and the scoring is just to compare the similarity of the text. The only value of such a system is that it is a waste of resources and is self-indulgent.
This is not only true for subnet 1, but also for other subnets which also have serious meaninglessness problems."

how would you guys respond to this?

 What they are basically refuting is the need for benchmarking, or its value. They should take that up with everyone doing AI research.

Secondly, we mitigate the risk of data leakage (when models have already 'trained' on the benchmarks) in new and novel ways:
1. Infinite dataset size
2. Ambiguity (roleplay & paraphrasing)
We are also evaluating the capabilities of miners at effective tool use, using high quality reference answers which are themselves factually robust.
Proof of work, by definition, is a verification mechanism to ensure that miners are able to carry out the required intelligence tasks.

## 🚀 Release Announcement: Prompting Version 2.3.0 🚀 

Hello @apex・1 community,

We are excited to announce the release of version 2.3.0, bringing Llama3 70B and date-qa improvements to the SN1 distributed intelligence!
https://github.com/macrocosm-os/prompting/releases/tag/v2.3.0

## What's New?
**Prompting is now hosted on Macrocosmos GitHub. The new validator repository will be located  at https://github.com/macrocosm-os/prompting, alongside other Macrocosmos initiatives. All future updates will be released there, so consider that https://github.com/opentensor/prompting is now https://github.com/macrocosm-os/prompting.**

As mentioned last week, we are upgrading the SN1 validators' base model to keep up with the latest changes in the open-source AI community, moving from the SOLAR-10.7B-Instruct-v1.0 LLM to the Llama3-70B-Instruct model.

## What does this mean?
**For Validators: **Increased GPU power will be necessary. We recommend upgrading to an A100 80GB GPU to support the initial deployment of Llama3 70B and future updates. Additionally, we have introduced two new parameters for validators to ease deployment across various hardware configurations:
- `--neuron.gpus`: Specifies the number of GPUs to be used during vllm load. Default is set to 1.
- `--neuron.llm_max_allowed_memory_in_gb`: Specifies the maximum allowed memory for vllm load. Default is set to 60 GB.

**For Miners:** This update introduces a new reference point that will naturally increase incentives for miners aligned with Llama3 70B. The challenges and references will now be generated by Llama3, meaning that miners aligned with this model's quality will be more incentivized.
Additionally, the new date-qa doesn't rely on the same dataset as the previous iteration, so if you're relying on a database for previous date-qa context retrieval, your scores will take a large hit.

**Next Steps:**
As discussed last week, we strongly recommend incorporating streaming capabilities into your miners to support future application back-ends. To support this, we are implementing a reward model that includes a penalty term based on a defined `max_tokens_per_chunk` parameter set in the validator. Miners who exceed this limit by returning responses in a single streaming chunk will incur penalties.
Additionally, we are exploring the possibility of upgrading the quantization of the new base validator model from 4 bits to 8 bits. We will keep you updated on our progress.

Happy coding!

In the coming 2 weeks after this release, we will begin adding benchmarking to effectively monitor the performance of miners in SN1 and allow the wider public to compare us to other SOTA open source models

New Tasks:
We will be adding a number of new tasks which will challenge miners to innovate and allow us to create better rounded systems. These include in the first iteration:
- Programming
- Information Retrieval
- Direct Inference

More information about these tasks will be released as we’re beginning to implement them and we will give miners sufficient time ahead of release to prepare their codebase for the arrival of new tasks.
